🌐 Understanding URLs

Module: Web Security
Lesson: Day 2

---

Introduction

Every website on the Internet is accessed using a URL (Uniform Resource Locator).

A URL is much more than just a website address. It contains valuable information about where a resource is located and how the browser should access it.

For a web developer, a URL helps navigate a website.

For a penetration tester, a URL is often the first place to look for vulnerabilities.

---

What is a URL?

A URL (Uniform Resource Locator) is the address used to locate a resource on the Internet.

Example:

```text
https://blog.example.com:443/articles/security?id=15&sort=new#comments
```

Every part of this URL has a specific purpose.

---

URL Structure

```text
https://blog.example.com:443/articles/security?id=15&sort=new#comments

│       │               │   │                  │                 │
│       │               │   │                  │                 └── Fragment
│       │               │   │                  └──────────────────── Query Parameters
│       │               │   └────────────────────────────────────── Path
│       │               └────────────────────────────────────────── Port
│       └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── Domain
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── Protocol
```

---

1. Protocol (Scheme)

The protocol tells the browser how communication should happen.

Example:

```text
https://
```

Common protocols:

| Protocol | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| HTTP | Transfers web pages without encryption |
| HTTPS | Secure communication using TLS |
| FTP | File Transfer |
| SSH | Secure remote login |

Today, almost every website uses HTTPS.

---

2. Domain Name

The domain is the human-readable name of a website.

Example:

```text
google.com
```

Instead of remembering an IP address, users simply remember the domain name.

DNS converts the domain into an IP address.

Examples:

```text
google.com

github.com

amazon.com

tryhackme.com
```

---

3. Subdomain

A subdomain is a subdivision of the main domain.

Example:

```text
mail.google.com
```

Here,

```text
mail
```

is the subdomain.

Examples:

| URL | Subdomain |
|------|-----------|
| mail.google.com | mail |
| drive.google.com | drive |
| docs.google.com | docs |

Each subdomain usually provides a different service while belonging to the same organization.

---

4. Top-Level Domain (TLD)

The Top-Level Domain is the last part of the domain name.

Examples:

```text
.com

.org

.edu

.gov

.in

.uk
```

Example:

```text
google.com
```

Here,

```text
.com
```

is the TLD.

---

5. Port

A port identifies which service on the server should receive the request.

Example:

```text
https://example.com:443
```

Here,

```text
443
```

is the port number.

Normally browsers automatically use:

| Protocol | Default Port |
|----------|--------------|
| HTTP | 80 |
| HTTPS | 443 |

Therefore, these two URLs are identical:

```text
https://google.com

https://google.com:443
```

---

6. Path

The path identifies the exact resource being requested from the server.

Example:

```text
/admin/login
```

Examples:

```text
/profile

/login

/dashboard

/images/logo.png
```

Think of the path like folders inside your computer.

---

7. Query Parameters

Query parameters send additional information to the server.

Example:

```text
/profile?id=25
```

Here,

```text
id = 25
```

means:

Show profile number 25.

Multiple parameters are separated using &amp;

Example:

```text
?id=15&sort=new&page=2
```

Parameter breakdown:

| Parameter | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| id | 15 |
| sort | new |
| page | 2 |

---

Why are Query Parameters Important?

Query parameters are one of the first things penetration testers examine.

Example:

```text
/profile?id=25
```

Questions a penetration tester asks:

- What happens if I change 25 to 26?
- Can I access another user's profile?
- Is the input properly validated?
- Can this parameter be manipulated?

Many real-world vulnerabilities begin with testing URL parameters.

---

8. Fragment

A fragment begins with:

```text
#
```

Example:

```text
#comments
```

The fragment never reaches the server.

It is used only by the browser to jump to a specific section of a webpage.

Example:

```text
page.html#contact
```

The browser scrolls directly to the Contact section.

---

Complete URL Breakdown

Example:

```text
https://blog.example.com:443/articles/security?id=15&sort=new#comments
```

| Component | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| Protocol | HTTPS |
| Subdomain | blog |
| Domain | example.com |
| Port | 443 |
| Path | /articles/security |
| Query Parameters | id=15&sort=new |
| Fragment | comments |

---

Real-World Analogy

Imagine ordering food online.

```text
https://pizza.com/order?size=large&topping=cheese
```

The restaurant receives:

| Parameter | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| Size | Large |
| Topping | Cheese |

Similarly, websites use query parameters to understand what information or resource the user is requesting.

---

Pentester's Mindset

When a penetration tester sees:

```text
https://bank.com/account?id=1001
```

Instead of simply opening the page, they ask:

- Can I change the ID?
- Does another user's data become visible?
- Is authorization being checked?
- Is the input validated?

This way of thinking often leads to discovering vulnerabilities like IDOR.

---

Key Points

- A URL is the address of a resource on the Internet.
- Every URL consists of multiple components.
- Domains are converted into IP addresses using DNS.
- The default port for HTTP is 80.
- The default port for HTTPS is 443.
- Query parameters send additional information to the server.
- Fragments are processed only by the browser.
- URL parameters are one of the most common attack surfaces in web security.

